<tr>
<td>
<h5>
FIM_ABBR aims to be a highly customizable and scriptable
image viewer targeted at users who are comfortable with software
like the VIM_ABBR text editor or the MUTT_ABBR mail user agent.


<br> &nbsp;<br>

Its sources derive from the <a href="http://www.bytesex.org">Fbi</a> image viewer by Gerd Hoffmann.
<BR>
It can display pictures on screen via the following video devices/modes:
<UL>
<LI>
   The <a href="http://www.linux.org">Linux</a>
   <a href="https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/fb/framebuffer.txt">framebuffer device</a> mode (graphically, see <a href="#screenshots">screenshots</a>).
</LI>
<LI>
   Under <a href="http://www.x.org">X/Xorg</a>, using the <a href="http://www.libsdl.org">SDL library</a> mode (graphically, see <a href="#screenshots">screenshots</a>).
</LI>
<LI>
   Under <a href="http://www.x.org">X/Xorg</a>, using the <a href="http://docs.enlightenment.org/api/imlib2/html/">Imlib2 library</a> mode (graphically, see <a href="#screenshots">screenshots</a>).
</LI>
<LI>
   In any textual console, using the <a href="http://aa-project.sourceforge.net/aalib">AAlib</a> Ascii Art library mode (rendering into text, see <a href="#screenshots">screenshots</a>).
</LI>
</UL>
<BR>

The right video mode gets auto-detected or selected at runtime, and may be opted in/out before build at configure time, if desired.

<br> &nbsp;<br>

<a href="FWP">FIM</a> is free software
(see <a href="#license">licensing info</a>)
and it is richly documented 
(see the <a href="#docs">documentation section</a>).
<br> &nbsp;<br>

FIM_ABBR's official web page is hosted on Savannah: <a href="HOMEPAGE">HOMEPAGE</a>
<br> &nbsp;<br>

FIM_ABBR's official mirror for stable releases is located on Savannah mirror network: <a href="MIRROR">MIRROR</a>
<br> &nbsp;<br>

FIM_ABBR's official mailing list is at: <a href="MAILINGLIST">MAILINGLIST</a>
<br> &nbsp;<br>


FIM_ABBR is an idea by
Michele Martone, although inspiration has been drawn
from other softwares as well as from certain science fiction movie scenes.
&nbsp;<br>


<br> &nbsp;<br>
You can support FIM_ABBR by supporting the <a href="http://savannah.nongnu.org/">Savannah project</a>, whom network kindly hosts FIM_ABBR repositories.

<br> &nbsp;<br>

</h5>
</td>
